We like designing sites with full-width content areas, but really dislike all the extra markup required to make it work. Chris Coyier wrote an excellent article about CSS pseudo elements used to create full-width color areas, but we want full width images and we want it in Sass! Here’s how you can adopt the <a href="http://css-tricks.com/full-browser-width-bars/">full-width color technique</a> to create a mixin for full-width images.
<h2>The Markup:</h2>
<pre class="prettyprint"><code class="language-html">
&lt;section&gt;
  &lt;h1&gt;  Anything can go here!&lt;/h1&gt;
  &lt;p&gt; Once we apply styles, this content will fit inside our full width container, but its background will spread all the way across the browser viewport.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/section&gt;
</code></pre>
We need to define a placeholder class. Think of Sass placeholders as an object that holds any class definition. It will never show the class name in your compiled stylesheet, but it can be extended into other classes or mixins.
<h2>Placeholder Class:</h2>
<pre class="prettyprint"><code>
%full-width-content-holder {
  position: relative;
  display: inline-block;
  width: 100%;
  &amp;:before, &amp;:after {
    content: '';
    position: absolute;
    top: 0;
    bottom: 0;
    width: 999px;
  }
  &amp;:after {
    right: 100%;
  }
  &amp;:before {
    left: 100%;
  }
}
</code></pre>
We use this to set the parent element as relative and create empty, absolute positioned pseudo elements to its left and right. Note that we've set it inline-block with a 100% width. This is to clear any floats we may use, as a traditional clearfix will overwrite our pseudo elements. Now we can create our mixin to use and reuse to our hearts desire! You may notice this doesn’t apply any background styles. It simply sets the stage so we can call specific background elements in our mixin defined below.

Let’s define our mixin which gets called on any selected element later on. It will take one argument called $image-url. When the mixin is called, we’ll replace $image-url with a unique background image.
<h2>Define a Mixin:</h2>
<pre class="prettyprint"><code class="language-css">

@mixin full-image($image-url) {

}
</code></pre>
Inside of here we can extend our placeholder class and describe background styles for all three elements.
<h2>The Complete Mixin:</h2>
<pre class="prettyprint"><code class="language-css">

@mixin full-image($image-url) {
  @extend %full-width-content-holder;
    background: url($image-url) no-repeat center center fixed;
    background-size: cover;
  &amp;:after {
    background: inherit;
  }
  &amp;:before {
    background: inherit;
  }
}

</code></pre>
In order for our three elements to cohesively share the same background image, we must set the attachment property as fixed and the size as cover. The position values here (center, top, bottom, etc.) can change as needed, as long as they match in each rule. <a href="https://twitter.com/kyle_unzicker">Kyle Unzicker</a> pointed out that one can use "background: inherit" on the pseudo elements to avoid repeating ourselves.

Finally, because our pseudo elements are so large, we need to crop the rendered document at the browser's viewport by removing overflow-x from the html and body elements.
<h2>The Final Touch:</h2>
<pre class="prettyprint"><code class="language-css">

html, body {
  overflow-x: hidden;
}

</code></pre>
Now we can call this mixin as many times as we’d like to in our styles.
<pre class="prettyprint"><code class="language-css">

section {
	@include full-image('img/my-background-image.jpg');
}
</code></pre>
This will set <em>section</em> as relative, create and arrange two absolute positioned pseudo elements and apply the background-image url as a full-width, fixed attachment.

